'''Uneo ni Masu Takehaniyasu Shrine''' (畝尾坐健土安神社) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Kashihara, Nara|ja|橿原市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Japan. It is situated at the northwestern foothills of {{ill|Mount Amanokagu|ja|天香具山|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. To the southwest, adjacent to the shrine, stands another {{ill|Shikinai-sha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|qq=draft|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the {{ill|Uneo Tsutamoto Shrine|ja|畝尾都多本神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. In the year 1446 (Bunan 3), the shrine was recorded in the ''Washū Five Districts Shrine Registry'' (和州五郡神社神名帳大略注解) as one of the "Four Shrines of Amanokagu" (天香山坐四處神社), alongside {{ill|Amanokaguyama Shrine|ja|天香山坐櫛真命神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Sakado Shrine (Amano-Iwato Shrine)|ja|坂門神社 (天岩戸神社)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Uneo Tsutamoto Shrine|ja|畝尾都多本神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<ref>[https://genbu.net/data/yamato/tutamoto_title.htm Uneo Tsutamoto Shrine]</ref>.

== History ==

According to the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'', in the pre-ascension records of {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, under the entry for the 20th day of the second month of the year ''Kinoe-Mi'' (己未), it is stated:

''"In the ninth month of the previous autumn, the Emperor secretly took sacred clay from Mount Amanokagu and crafted eighty ''hirakame'' (sacred earthenware). He then purified himself and performed a ritual to the gods, thereby securing the stability of the land. Because of this, the place where the clay was gathered was named 'Haniyasu'"''.

It is believed that the deity enshrined here is the spirit of the land itself, which was revered in Haniyasu. 

According to the ''{{ill|Yamato-shi|ja|大和志|1=Five Kinai Chronicles|lt=Yamato-shi|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'', the shrine was once referred to as "Amaterasu-Ōmikami" (天照大神), and during the Edo period, it was called "Amaterasu Shrine" (天照大神社).

== deity ==

The shrine enshrines {{ill|Haniyasu-hime|ja|波邇夜須毘売神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a goddess born from the excrement of {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊邪那美|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who suffered burns and perished after giving birth to the fire god {{ill|Kagutsuchi|ja|迦具土命|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It is said that from her bodily fluids—urine, feces, and vomit—various deities were born, with Haniyasu-hime emerging from her feces.

