''"In the ninth month of the previous autumn, the Emperor secretly took sacred clay from Mount Amanokagu and crafted eighty ''hirakame'' (sacred earthenware). He then purified himself and performed a ritual to the gods, thereby securing the stability of the land. Because of this, the place where the clay was gathered was named 'Haniyasu'"''.

It is believed that the deity enshrined here is the spirit of the land itself, which was revered in Haniyasu. 

According to the ''{{ill|Yamato-shi|ja|大和志|1=Five Kinai Chronicles|lt=Yamato-shi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato-shi|13=User:Immanuelle/Five Kinai Chronicles|qq=}}'', the shrine was once referred to as "Amaterasu-Ōmikami" (天照大神), and during the Edo period, it was called "Amaterasu Shrine" (天照大神社).

== deity ==

The shrine enshrines {{ill|Haniyasu-hime|ja|波邇夜須毘売神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haniyasu-hime|qq=}}, a goddess born from the excrement of {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊邪那美|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanami|qq=}}, who suffered burns and perished after giving birth to the fire god {{ill|Kagutsuchi|ja|迦具土命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kagutsuchi|qq=}}. It is said that from her bodily fluids—urine, feces, and vomit—various deities were born, with Haniyasu-hime emerging from her feces.

